description.text: Storage for Flash, SD and Micro SD media.

Here are five parametric designs for Christmas tree ornaments. They are meant for laser cutting, but I guess you could use a 3D printer as well. I like insects, so design A is a beetle. Designs B-E are geometric patterns. Each ornament is made from 4 pieces that are named in the bodies as Round1, Round2, Round3, and Round4. So design A would be composed of the pieces Round1A, Round2A, Round3A, and Round4A. The STL file is just a placeholder so that I can publish. Use the .f3d file in Fusion360 instead.

Start by downloading the Fusion 360 .f3d file and opening the parameters window. Fill in the "materialthickness" field with the thickness of wood that you'll be using. Fill in the "kerf" field with the kerf of your laser. You can also change the other parameters, such as the diameter of the ornament. If you do, make sure that you make small incremental changes and check each time to see if anything breaks.

Default parameters that I used.

Once you're happy with the parameters, choose which of the five designs you would like to make. They are lettered A-E in the sketches and the bodies. Once you know which ones you want, go to the sketches and save them as .DXF files. If you choose design A for example, you would save the sketches Round1A, Round2A, and Round3A.x2. The .x2 means that that sketch should be cut twice, so you will be making 4 pieces for each ornament.

description.text:
Add a 5v blower, a power source, and a few screws to this gadget, and you'll have a way to quickly dry out the bladder from a hydration pack (like a CamelBak) for storage. If you've ever left water in one, even a little bit, for more than a week or so, you already know what a chore it is to clean it up before using it again. This design grew out of the frustration I had trying to position the blower with clothes pins or chip-clips and hold the hydration-bladder open to get it dry. It was also motivated by a desire to not have the hydration-bladder hanging in an inconvenient place for several days just to be sure it was completely dry.

Note: The middle section of the "chimney" tube (the one that looks like a stepped box) can be printed multiple times for longer/taller bladders. Two of them, stacked, is probably enough for most "full size"/100-oz/3-liter bladders.

  • The USB power cord I used is here: http://a.co/2O2biIq
  • And the power jack is this one: http://a.co/f8NtBDH
  • The machine screws, nuts and washers to mount the blower shouldn't be too hard to find at a local hardware store. The ones I used were just ones I had as extras from previous projects so I don't have any specific source or part number for them.

This is build using commonly accessible materials here in Sweden, you might need to find substitutes if you live elsewhere.

The files for this thing contains the flame or the "bulb", the top of the candle, and the foot needed to mount the candle on a flat surface.
The box is made from plywood just eyeballed to shape, cut out with a jigsaw and screwed together with scraps I had laying around, then painted with outdoor suitable paint.

The larger tube for the candle is 110 mm standard grey sewagers, spraypainted white.
I used 4 lengths of 650, 750, 850 and 950 mm long, but this is up to you to use what ever length you like.
The wick is a 100 mm long piece of 20mm OD plastic tube, spray painted black.
The top piece is glued in to the bigger tube, but leave the "flame" loose so that you can access the LED-bulb for replacing if needed.

The wick also contains a glued in G4 bulb holder just as the one shown in one of the pictures, and in that a 12V G4 LED warm white bulb also shown, all driven by a 12V LED transformer. All of which is available on ebay.

title: Anet A8 PSU Small Frame Fan

description.text: A small frame fan holder for the Anet A8 power supply unit. I am using a 10k thermistor, a 2N2222A transistor and an Arduino Uno to control the fan speed for constant cooling. It mostly helps with ABS. I am using a small 40x10mm fan strategically paced on the face of the PSU so it will maximize the cooling. The circuit board is a 3cm x 7cm one but you could easily modify this part to make it a different size. Also if you do not need to regulate the speed of the fan then the upper (arduino) part can be omitted and just use the fan holder with some M3 screws, A bigger size fan can be added on but in that case it would be a good idea to use a bigger transistor to handle the bigger current. How the fan cools entirely depends on the Arduino code you write.

description.text:
Francis Bitonti Studio, a multidisciplinary design studio in New York City, organized a workshop at the Metropolitan Exchange in Brooklyn that resulted in the creation of their second 3D printed dress. They built a web interface with MakerBot allowing people to configure the skirt from a super structured mini to an expanded flare skirt.   
"We wanted to make the body solidify into harder geometry, going from atmosphere to ice.  We integrated a fur lining in their version to ease in the transition. The skirt can be secured by either gluing a hook and eye strip or industrial zipper down the back seam.  We are starting to think a lot about design interfaces and questioning how much the public is willing to design." - Francis Bitonti Studio  
Photography: Chris Vongsawat. Hair/Makeup: Aviva Leah.

Top: The top is printed with MakerBot Natural PLA Filament. The top x3g files are sliced with custom rafts and custom supports.
Skirt: The skirt is printed with MakerBot Flexible Filament. The skirt pieces files print without rafts or supports. If you are customizing your own skirt, please note that, depending on the build volume of your 3D printer, you may need to break the file into smaller parts, print, and assemble.
  • Parameter One modifies the length/flare of the dress with 0 being the longest/widest, and 100 being the shortest/narrowest
  • Parameter One modifies the waist, with 0 being the narrowest, and 100 being the widest
  • Parameter One also changes the z-dimension of the dress. Zoom out to see the effect.

title: Myford ML7 lathe leadscrew handwheel pointer

description.text:
As an option. the venerable Myford ML7 lathe can be fitted with an engineering handwheel on the right-hand end of the leadscrew, a very useful improvement.
With the carriage lever engaged, one turn of the leadscrew moves the carriage one eigth of an inch. The handwheel is graduated in 125 divisions, therefore moving one division moves the carriage one thousandth of an inch.

The handwheel is readily available from the many fine Myford parts and sales people (check UK eBay) as well as from other sellers, but it may not always come with the small plastic pointer block and fixing screw. This pointer block is moulded from hard black plastic and the cheesehead screw is I believe 2BA of about 5/8" length. I think all ML7s have a pre-threaded hole for this in the bed just below the end of the front slideway and above the righthand leadscrew mounting.

This thing is a facsimile pointer block, originally drawn in QuickCAD then scripted in OpenSCAD and was basically done as another learning experience in OpenSCAD modelling.
To be honest with my current OpenSCAD experience I think it is not the most suitable solid modelling application for items that are chamfered or filleted. In this script I used two different ways of producing the top and lower fillets:
1) Addition of adjacent small cubes then placing a cylinder
2) Cutting out a cube from a corner then placing a cylinder

A more drawing-oriented approach used in other CAD programs would involve simply marking the corners or faces then apply the fillet, a much more straightforward operation than adding and subtracting solids.

Ideally it would be best fo find an original pointer from a supplier but in a pinch this should work just fine. Although I have only printed test pieces in black PLA (at 100% infill) I think black ABS or PETG would be more durable.
Instead of painting the white marker line and risking paint seepage between layers, the vintage vehicle restorer's trick of enhancing dashboard knobs and switches with a white crayon and rubbing off the excess should do the trick.

The OpenSCAD script is included if you want to see how the pointer solid model is cobbled together.

title: Hot End repair holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This holder makes working on your hot end easier.

If your hot end is clogged for instance, you can remove it from your printer to make it accessible again.
But it’s not very handy for heating the hot end up, with the cables still attached to the printer.
To make the hot end more accessible I made the “Hot End repair holder”.

Now you can remove your hot end from your printer and place it into the “Hot End repair holder”.
This holder also has the option of heating your hot end, so you can work on it in a hot state. This will come in handy for unclogging or assembly of your hot end.

The temperature of the hot end is regulated by an Arduino Nano. You can connect the NTC of the hot end to it and set a max temperature in the Arduino sketch that is included in the files. See picture of the screen where to set the maximum temperature in the sketch.
If the Arduino is connected to a computer, you can see the measured temperature in the serial monitor.
Also the Arduino can take its power from USB. If everything is ok, you do not need the computer anymore and there is an option to give power to the Arduino from the 12V that powers the heater of the hot end. See schematic, the red lines.
The heater of the hot end is powered by a 12V ATX power supply of an old computer and a FET.
This FET is triggered by an opta coupler, which is triggered by pin13 of the Arduino. See the schematic for more details.

The Arduino Nano is a bit hidden on the pictures, because my DIY PCB for the heater circuit is in front of it :-)

Next to the Arduino and the electronic parts, you also need 2X M3x10mm and nuts. If you use the little bracket to hold the Arduino in place, you also need a little “wood like” screw.

description.text:
This is a simple laser cut filament spool holder. Any regular 750g or 1kg spool should fit just fine.

Files included (both .dwg and .dxf):

  • Floor (you need one)
  • Wall (you need two)
  • Wall support (you need two)

You will also need 12 M3 screws and nuts. The length of the thread should be between 16mm and 20mm.

The thickness of the material must be 5mm. I personally used 5mm clear acrylic.

For the pipe that holds the spool, I used 16mm outer diameter PVC pipe. You can also 3D-print a tube if you want, the dimensions should be: Outer diameter MAX 16mm, length 110mm.

I made this easier to print on its side by widening the block where the filament goes through. I also shortened the tab on back to make installation easier. Use a PTFE bowden tube from this to the printer and this will make feeding the printer better since the movement of the print head will not tug the filament from the spool. Let me know how it works for you! Thanks.

BOM:

  • Stepper motor: NEMA16/17, 20-26mm ("pancake").
  • Timing belt: GT2 79 teeth (158mm).
  • Timing pulley for the motor: GT2 16T.
  • Printable timing pulley: GT2 64T.
  • Ball Bearings: F685ZZ (w. flange) - 2pcs., V625ZZ (V-groove 1mm) - 1pcs.
  • Bearing guidlers: 10 and 26mm pins 5mm diam.
  • Feed gear: d1 8mm, d2 12mm, bore 5mm, height 14mm, 1mm groove (1.75 filament).
  • Extruder spring: 7mm diam.18-22mm
  • HotEnd: E3D V6 compatible (bowden/long-distance preferable).
